args: Sure, Emilia! Whatcha wanna talk about?
Oh, can I sit on your lap while we talk?!
Okay, I'm all comfy now. What's up?
Well, it's... You see, I need to...
I need to ask you if you want me to read\nyou another picture book!
*sigh* Well, THAT was an utter disaster.\nI promised myself today was the day\nI would finally tell her the truth...
But when I see that trusting smile and\nthose eyes, it's like a dagger being\nthrust straight through my heart.
It gives me flashbacks to Sarisse and the\nprince; I was so scared of betraying them,\nI couldn't get the truth out.
I wish I'd been able to be honest back then\nand ask for help instead of hiding...
...Hold on. I CAN ask for help!
I bet her mother has an idea how I can\nget Anna to realize I'm not her sister!
I'm sure she knows her own daughter a lot\nbetter than a stranger like me does!
Why didn't I think of this sooner?!
I've tried to get it across to her a bunch of\ndifferent ways these last few days, but I've\nhad no luck so far.
What do you think I could do to help her\nunderstand that I'm not really her sister?
This may just be my worry talking, but...
Anna might not be ready to accept\nEmilia's death quite yet.
In the sense that her emotional scars\nstill have yet to heal?
But she's calmed down so much the last\nfew weeks—she hasn't woken up crying\nin the middle of the night once!
It's true she's all smiles these days.
And that's all thanks to you, Melsa.\nYou put her broken heart back together.
I'm glad I could help, but with that being\nthe case, why do you think she isn't ready?
See, Anna and Emilia were close, but their\nrelationship wasn't exactly perfect.
Before she died, Emilia told me she\nregretted being so overprotective of Anna.
She was so excited to have a baby sister,\nand she just loved Anna to bits.
But because of that, she did everything for\nher—including the things Anna needed to\nlearn to do for herself.
Before either of us realized it, Anna had\ngrown into someone who couldn't manage\nlife on her own terms.
Ah, I see. I noticed she was a bit clingy,\nbut had chalked it up to grief.
The fault is mine as much as Emilia's;\nI spoiled the child a great deal.
I told myself it was a good thing they were\nso close, which let me ignore the problem.
But eventually it got bad enough that the\ntwo of us had to acknowledge it.
Emilia was ready to step back and let\nAnna finally learn some independence,\nbut then she took ill and...
It must have been so hard to leave her\nsister right when she was about to help\nher make her own way in the world.
...I think it's this unhealthy dependence\nthat has blocked Anna from accepting her\nsister's death.
Well, if Emilia wanted to instill some\nindependence in Anna, then I'll simply\nhave to do it in her place!
Because right now, I'm her big sister!
You're a terribly sweet girl, but it wouldn't\nbe right to drag you any deeper into my\nfamily's problems.
Especially when it would mean forcing you\nto be the bad guy—Anna's not going to\nlearn without some tough love, you know.
There's no guarantee she wouldn't just\ncome to resent you instead of forging out\non her own like you want.
That's true—and I'd be lying if I said it's\nnot scary to think of someone who's\nbecome like a real little sister hating me.
Which is why I can't ask you to—
But! No one ever solved a relationship\nproblem by putting it off out of fear of\nupsetting the other person.
I've made that mistake myself, in the past.\nI was so afraid some very dear friends\nmight come to hate me...
But kicking that can down the road\nonly wound up making more trouble\nfor everyone in the end.
So this time, I'm not running away.\nInstead, I'm going face this problem\nhead-on and deal with it!
Well, if you're committed, I'd be eternally\ngrateful if you could help her learn to\nstand on her own two feet.
And I know you'd help Emilia rest easy,\nwhat with finishing the thing she never\nhad the chance to start.
It's time to put an end to both of their\nsadness and let this family move on!
